                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout style="vertical" rend="arris_up">The Ogham inscription starts from the bottom left edge of the stone and continues upwards, along the top edge, and terminates two-thirds of the way along the top. The rectangular pillar is also inscribed with a roman-letter inscription in three lines reading vertically downwards (Edwards 2007, 180).</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                          <handDesc>
                            <handNote>Both inscriptions are <rs type="execution" key="pocked" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/11.html">pocked</rs> and described as <q>deeply incised with a punch</q> (Edwards 2007, 180). The tail of the first G in line 3 of the roman-letter inscription extends over the angle of the stone, marking the beginning of the ogham inscription. The distinctive forms of the S and F ane closely paralleled on St Dogmaels 1 (W-PEM-001; Edwards 2007, 460-463); a similar F is also found on Mathry 1 (W-PEM-016; Edwards 2007, 380-383). 
                                <height></height>
                            </handNote>
